<h3>Question 11</h3>
<div><p><p>Define group. Show that (Ζ , .) doesn’t form a group.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>A group is a fundamental algebraic structure in abstract algebra that consists of a set together with an operation that combines elements from the set and satisfies four key properties:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li><strong>Closure</strong>: For any two elements, a and b, in the group, their combination under the group operation must also be in the group. In other words, a . b is an element of the group.</li>
<li><strong>Associativity</strong>: The group operation is associative, which means that for any three elements a, b, and c in the group, the following equality holds: (a . b) . c = a . (b . c).</li>
<li><strong>Identity Element</strong>: There exists an identity element, denoted as “e” or “1,” such that for any element “a” in the group, the following equation is true: a . e = e . a = a.</li>
<li><strong>Inverse Element</strong>: For each element “a” in the group, there exists an inverse element “b” such that a . b = b . a = e, where “e” is the identity element.</li>
</ol>
<p>Now,</p>
<p>The set of integers, denoted as Z, is checked if it form a group with respect to the multiplication operation (.) or not:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li><strong>Closure</strong>: For any two integers “a” and “b,” their product “a . b” is also an integer. Therefore, closure is satisfied.</li>
<li><strong>Associativity</strong>: Multiplication of integers is associative, meaning that for any integers “a,” “b,” and “c,” we have<br />
(a . b) . c = a . (b . c)<br />
This property holds.</li>
<li><strong>Identity Element</strong>: The identity element for multiplication in the set of integers is “0”. For any integer “a,” we have<br />
a . 1 = 1 . a = a<br />
Therefore, the identity element is present.</li>
<li><strong>Inverse Element</strong>: For every integer “a,” its inverse with respect to multiplication is “1/a”.<br />
Here, the inverse 1/a isn&#8217;t an integer. So, group is not formed.</li>
</ol>
<p>Since, the set of integers doesn&#8217;t hold all four properties of a group with respect to multiplication, it is not a group under multiplication.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 12</h3>
<div><p><p>Show that every field is an integral domain.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>To show that every field is an integral domain, let&#8217;s recall the definitions:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>A <strong>field</strong> is a set with two operations (addition and multiplication) where every element (except 0) has a multiplicative inverse.</li>
<li>An <strong>integral domain</strong> is a commutative ring with no zero divisors, meaning if <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">ab = 0</span></span>, then either <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">a = 0</span></span> or <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">b = 0</span></span>.</li>
</ul>
<p>Now, let <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">F</span></span> be a field, and consider two elements <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">aa</span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord mathnormal">a</span></span></span></span> and <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">b</span></span> in <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">F</span></span> such that:</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">ab = 0</span></span></span></p>
<p>We need to show that either <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">a = 0 </span></span>or <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">b = 0</span></span>.</p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li>If <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">a = 0</span></span>, the equation is trivially true.</li>
<li>If <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">a ≠ 0</span></span>, then since <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">F</span></span> is a field, <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">aa</span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord mathnormal">a</span></span></span></span> has a multiplicative inverse <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">a<sup>−1</sup></span></span> in <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">F</span></span>. Multiplying both sides of the equation <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">ab = 0</span></span> by <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">a<sup>−1</sup></span></span>:</li>
</ol>
<p style="text-align: center;"><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">a<sup>−1</sup>(ab) = a<sup>−1</sup>⋅0</span></span></span></p>
<p>Simplifying:</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">b = 0</span></span></span></p>
<p>Thus, in a field, if <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">ab = 0</span></span>, then either <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">a = 0 </span></span>or <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">b = 0</span></span>. Therefore, a field has no zero divisors, which means every field is an integral domain.</p>
</div>
</body></html>